Individuals' educational access and results are greatly influenced by their family and community. A child's family and community may give them with tools and support that will help them thrive in school, such as access to books and educational materials, encouragement to seek education, and financial assistance for college. A child's family and community, on the other hand, might provide challenges to educational access and achievement, such as poverty, a lack of access to excellent schools, and prejudice. Policies and initiatives focusing on parental and community educational involvement may assist address problems of equity, diversity, and inclusion by offering support and resources to families and communities that would not otherwise have access to them. Programs that give financial aid for college or support and tools to help parents navigate the education system, for example, may help level the playing field for children from low-income homes. Programs aimed at increasing parental and community involvement in education may also contribute to a more inclusive and equitable educational environment. Programs that give parent education and training on how to support their child's education, for example, may assist empower parents to advocate for their child's education and become more active in the educational system. Furthermore, community-based initiatives such as tutoring or mentorship may assist to improve educational results for kids from low-income neighborhoods by offering extra support and resources that can help reduce the achievement gap. In conclusion, policies and programs focusing on parental and community educational engagement can play an important role in addressing issues of equity, diversity, and inclusion by providing support and resources to families and communities that might not otherwise have access to them, as well as increasing parental and community engagement in education. 